<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0290</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:DomestosSans-Normal; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Forum of Private Business – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#006038; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This evidence is submitted from the Forum of Private Business. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Forum of Private Business is a business membership organisation. Members are typically small, private sector employers. We offer various services and products to members, of which advocacy to policy makers is just </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">one.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">All figures in this response, unless otherwise stated, come from the Forum’s Cost of Compliance report, released this summer. A copy of that report has been sent with this response. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#006038; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#006038; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">General</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">he cost of compliance for micro, small and medium-sized employers (1-250 staff) has risen to £18.2 billion in total, with a total of £11.3bn for internal salaried costs and £6.9bn in external support costs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This is equivalent to £14,800 per small business (£9,200 in internal costs and £5,600 in external costs). However the cost for each business owner feels much higher as the opportunity costs of internal compliance are £37.8bn or almost three times the actual salaried costs. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Cost of compliance per employee drops as the number of staff increases from £3,900 per person for businesses with less than 5 employees to £500 per employee for firms with over 50 staff.</span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The cost of employing one employee is estimated as costing businesses £1,970 or 8 hours in internal time (£1,845) and £125 in external costs. This demonstrates the larger impact of compliance on smaller businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Bill does achieve its purpose of reducing the regulatory burden on businesses but at £10m a year, that is far from a substantial saving. Over the next few years businesses will be asked to take on new responsibilities in managing joint parental leave, managing competing requests for flexible working and paying an initial 3% more to every employee’s pension pot. In the wider context of the ‘cost of compliance’ the Government’s removal of these measures pales in comparison to those coming in. So, whilst the Bill may achieve its individual purpose, the Government’s regulatory program more widely is questionable.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Forum of Private Business would argue that whilst there has been a focus on both the stock and flow of regulation there remain deep seated problems in understanding the regulatory impact on small businesses. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">33% of businesses feel there has been a decrease in their control of the organisation as a result of regulatory compliance. As a result, three in four businesses would like to see a general reduction in the number of laws that they have to comply with. 56% of businesses would also like to see the number of regulatory bodies reduced. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#006038; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#006038; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Power to disapply legislation no longer of practical use </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If the new power provides a quicker removal of anachronistic regulations then it is to be welcomed. It would be of benefit however for ‘practical’ to be defined in order to better </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">justify the decision making process. The clauses seem to provide opportunity for concerns to be raised ahead of any final decision. The FPB feels the mechanisms set out for parliamentary oversight are adequate and appropriate? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#006038; font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A duty to have regard to the desirability of promoting economic growth</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">It is clear from responses to the consultation (and detailed in the Government’s own response) that some regulators believe they already promote economic growth. It is the FPB’s view that unless enshrined in legislation this will remain an optional focus of many regulators. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The proposal is not without its problems. Unless it is supplementing the civil service, the Government does not create jobs, as it so often claims. Instead, it can create a helpful framework in which job creation can take place. Likewise, a Government cannot directly create growth. Again, it can create the appropriate conditions in which growth can occur. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">To that end, there are worries around how a regulator might interpret a growth duty on the ground.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Forum of Private Business does not endorse the idea that a growth duty should be the overriding factor influencing regulators. Instead, it should be complementary to other duties. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The natural inclination would be towards a ‘power’ to promote economic growth but given other duties of regulators are statutory this seems too small a change. Given this, the FPB supports the use of primary legislation to introduce a duty for regulators to have a regard for growth. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FPB does not believe that a duty with </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">regard to “promoting economic growth” will compromise the independence of regulators, or that additional safeguards are required. This is because the duty is supported only as a complimentary one, not the overriding one. It will be up to individual regulators to justify their actions in their regard to growth in no different a way than they currently do. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The FPB does foresee some difficulties in the day-to-day practicality of implementing a duty towards economic growth. </span><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">For instance, there will be situations where a regulator might not be sure to which business to apply a regard towards growth. For example, should a regulator support the growth of a compliant business which is being undercut by local, non-compliant competitors by cracking down hard on those competitors? Alternatively, should the duty be towards the competitors, working with them to make them compliant and ensuring they do not go out of business. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">These kinds of questions will pose difficulties to regulators who would benefit from guidance in dealing with them. To this extent, the Forum of Private Business does believe that a form of guidance would be useful. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The Forum of Private Business believes a growth duty would reduce costs to business and remove a barrier to growth, even if that barrier is simply a perception one. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:DomestosSans-Normal; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>